We recommended that Management:
require the OIC – Municipal Accountant to prepare journal entry vouchers (JEV) to take up reconciling items already determined as book error;
exert extra effort to reconcile BRS of prior periods;
ensure bank reconciliation statements are prepared and regularly submitted to the Auditor for timely review/verification thereof;
coordinate with the OIC – Municipal Treasurer to determine the unreconciled amounts and trace those items that have no nature and breakdown; and
ensure that entries in cash in bank per books are reviewed thoroughly to avoid material errors in recording.

We recommended that Management:
ensure that all accountable officers are properly bonded before cash advances are granted to them;
direct and provide assistance, if necessary, to the OIC-Municipal Accountant in reconciling the balances of the cash advances accounts in order to reflect the correct amount in the financial statements of the LGU;
facilitate liquidation/settlement of the noted unliquidated cash advances especially those which are outstanding for more than 1 year, where the purpose/activity for which the cash advances were granted was already completed;
stop the practice of granting of cash advances for the procurement of goods and services which should be processed in accordance with the procurement law; and
establish and monitor controls to ensure the timely liquidation of cash advances through updated monthly aging of the same and sending demand letters to concerned AOs, to prevent accumulation of unliquidated balances at year-end.

We recommended that Management:

facilitate the submission of the SSMI together with the Distribution List of the goods consumed and distributed in CY 2020 to the Accounting Office in order to record the supplies and materials as expenses and drop the corresponding inventory accounts from the books; 

require the GSO/Inventory Committee to conduct physical count of inventory items on a semestral basis and prepare and submit the corresponding report to the Audit Team; 


require the GSO to prepare and submit the SSMI together with the supporting Requisition and Issue Slip (RIS) to the Accounting Office on a monthly basis for proper recording of consumed supplies and materials as expenses; and 

require the Municipal Accountant and GSO to maintain supplies ledger cards (SLC) and stock cards (SC), respectively, for each type of inventories and periodically reconcile the two records.

We recommended that Management:
facilitate the submission of the Summary of Supplies and Materials Issued (SSMI) together with the Distribution List of the goods consumed/distributed in CY 2020 to the Accounting Office in order to record the supplies and materials as expenses and drop the corresponding inventory accounts from the books;
require the GSO/Inventory Committee to conduct physical count of inventory items on a semestral basis and prepare and submit the corresponding report to the Audit Team;
require the GSO to prepare and submit the Summary of Supplies and Materials Issued (SSMI) together with the supporting Requisition and Issue Slip (RIS) to the Accounting Office on a monthly basis for proper recording of consumed supplies and materials as expenses; and
require the Municipal Accountant and GSO to maintain supplies ledger cards (SLC) and stock cards (SC), respectively, for each type of inventories and periodically reconcile the two records.

Recommendation:

We recommended that Management direct the Municipal Accountant to:

prepare the necessary adjusting journal entries in order to recognize the aforementioned infrastructure projects in the books;

record accumulated costs of infrastructure projects to construction in progress accounts or in the appropriate infrastructure assets upon completion; 

maintain required schedule and subsidiary ledgers as well as PPE ledger cards to properly account the ongoing and completed infrastructure assets of the LGU; and


ensure that completed projects under trust fund not yet recognized as infrastructure assets or any other PPE assets were properly identified, recorded and appropriately transferred to general fund.

Recommendation:

We recommended that Management direct the Municipal Treasurer to:

ensure that all collections are deposited intact to the depository bank and particularly demand for the immediate deposit of the amount of ₱5,103,619.38 otherwise institute appropriate legal measures to compel prompt deposit of said amount;
regularly and properly record in the Cashbook all collections and deposits made to allow for reconciliation of records of cash accounts between the MTO and Accounting Office; and ensure accuracy and completeness in the reporting and submission of Report of Collections and Deposit (RCD) and their supporting documents for proper and correct recording of collections and deposits in the books;

designate one each personnel from accounting and treasury office who shall work on the reconciliation of both records on a full-time basis to immediately establish correctness of actual undeposited collections; and

require the immediate relief of personnel involved in this irregularity until such time that full deposits are made.

Recommendation:

We recommended that the Management: 

employ constant follow up on the approval of the LGU’s SWM Plan as well as the establishment of the SLF for proper, clearer and systematic implementation of SWM and hasten the completion of SLF, respectively;


implement SWM PPAs as planned and strictly enforce planned SWM implementation strategies such as the approved ordinances, monitoring system and incentive programs; 



assign additional personnel/utility workers, if necessary, for monitoring and enforcement of SWM policies; 

intensify the EIC to households community on the importance of SWM; and 


direct the Solid Waste Management council, focal person and other responsible LGU personnel to coordinate and conduct regular meetings, to discuss issues and concern and updates regarding implementation of SWM PPAs.

We recommended and Management agreed to direct the Municipal Treasurer to:
ensure that all collections are deposited intact to the depository bank and particularly demand for the immediate deposit of the amount of ₱5,103,619.38 otherwise institute appropriate legal measures to compel prompt deposit of said amount;
regularly and properly record in the Cashbook all collections and deposits made to allow for reconciliation of records of cash accounts between the MTO and Accounting Office; and
ensure accuracy and completeness in the reporting and submission of Report of Collections and Deposit (RCD) and their supporting documents for proper and correct recording of collections and deposits in the books;
designate one each personnel from accounting and treasury office who shall work on the reconciliation of both records on a full-time basis to immediately establish correctness of actual undeposited collections; and
require the immediate relief of personnel involved in this irregularity until such time that full deposits are made.

We recommended that Management direct the Municipal Accountant to:
prepare the necessary adjusting journal entries in order to recognize the aforementioned infrastructure projects in the books;
record accumulated costs of infrastructure projects to construction in progress accounts or in the appropriate infrastructure assets upon completion;
maintain required schedule and subsidiary ledgers as well as PPE ledger cards to properly account the ongoing and completed infrastructure assets of the LGU; and
ensure that completed projects under trust fund not yet recognized as infrastructure assets or any other PPE assets were properly identified, recorded and appropriately transferred to general fund.

We recommend that the Management:

create or reiterate, if there are available policies on proper procedure of payment of payroll and inform responsible office heads, employees, JOs and casual workers for strict adherence thereto;

direct the Municipal Human Resource Management Officer to see to it that all employees have accomplished and submitted their respective DTRs and applications for leave to his office before payrolls are processed for payment and update/record any approved leave of absence to employees’ respective service records so that leave credits and any deductions thereof are properly accounted; and instruct the Municipal Accountant and Treasurer to ensure that all required documents are already approved and submitted before payment and recording.

We recommend that Management:

create a policy on proper procedure of payment of payroll and inform responsible office heads, employees, JOs and casual workers for strict adherence thereto; 

direct the Municipal HRMO to see to it that all DTRs, accomplishment reports and other required supporting documents to payroll as necessary are properly accomplished and completely signed by the payees and authorized signatories before processing for payment; and instruct the Municipal Accountant and Treasurer to ensure that all required documents are already approved and submitted before payment and recording.

The Audit Team recommended that Management:

direct the Municipal Accountant and GSO to adhere with the required accounting and recording of PPE and allot time to reconcile each other’s record by preparing supporting schedules and inventory reports for reliable presentation and reporting of PPE accounts;

direct the GSO to prepare/update the proper form and content of RPCPPE and Property Cards;

facilitate the assignment of property number stickers on all LGU property for proper monitoring and reporting of PPE accounts; and

direct concerned LGU’s personnel that all pertinent documents relative to acquisition of properties should be submitted to GSO for proper recording and update of inventory records/reports.

We recommended that Management:
adhere strictly with Section 3 of COA Circular No. 2009-001 and Section 4(6) of PD 1445 at all times and submit/attach complete contract documents and required supporting documents to government disbursements;
submit immediately the subject/needed lacking supporting documents to facilitate technical review and evaluation of the completed projects;
refrain from approving government claims with incomplete supporting documents.

We recommended that the Management:
employ constant follow up on the approval of the LGU’s SWM Plan as well as the establishment of the SLF for proper, clearer and systematic implementation of SWM and hasten the completion of SLF, respectively.
implement SWM PPAs as planned and strictly enforce planned SWM implementation strategies such as the approved ordinances, monitoring system and incentive programs;
assign additional personnel/utility workers, if necessary, for monitoring and enforcement of SWM policies;
intensify education information campaign to households community on the importance of SWM;
direct the SWM council, focal person and other responsible LGU personnel to coordinate and conduct regular meetings, when necessary to discuss issues and concern and updates regarding implementation of SWM PPAs; and
adopt additional specific revenue-generating measure to promote the viability of the LGU’s Solid Waste Management Plan.

We reiterate our previous audit recommendation that Management require the Municipal Accountant to:

a. Direct the immediate recording of all book reconciling items;

b. Update/Prepare timely and complete BRS of all depository bank accounts in accordance with COA Circular No. 96-011 and submit to the Auditor together with the copies of the JEVs supporting the adjustments already recorded in the books of accounts.
